 be one of musical scholarship’s intellectual touchstones for many years to come. Original, innovative, and sophisticated, their essays explore not only the implications of the "structural listening" model but also the alternative listening strategies that have developed in specific communities, often in response to twentieth-century Western music.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aMusicxPhilosophy and aesthetics. 0aMusicxSocial aspects. 0aMusical analysis. 0aMusical criticism. 0aPostmodernism. 7aMUSIC / Genres & Styles / Classical.2bisacsh  a20th century.  aanthology.  abeauty.  abeethoven.  acollection of essays.  alistening strategies.  alistening.  amodes of listening.  amtv.  amusic historians.  amusic scholars.  amusic students.  amusic textbooks.  amusic theorists.  amusic theory.  amusical communities.  amusical meaning.  amusical scholarship.  amusical structure.  anonfiction essays.  anonfiction.  apostmodern modes of hearing.  apostmodern theory.  astructural hearing.  atheoretical perspective.  awestern music.1 aAttinello, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDell'Antonio, Andrew, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDell’Antonio, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDubiel, Joseph, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFink, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLe Guin, Elisabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLevitz, Tamara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMaus, Fred Everett, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMorris, Mitchell, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/voc